  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although \"The Economy and Meaningfulness\" has not garnered formal citations or substantial digital mentions, its pedagogical relevance suggests a potential role in educational settings, underpinning discussions of sustainable economic practices.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published by Peter Lang B in 2019, \"The Economy and Meaningfulness\" offers insights into economic frameworks that prioritize meaningful engagement and sustainability. As of now, the book has not attracted citations or external mentions in platforms such as Wikipedia or Reddit, highlighting a gap in broader public discourse. However, the inferred role of being a \"pedagogical anchor\" points toward its utility as a resource in educational contexts, evidenced by its library holdings across four institutions.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's mention under the \"sustainability & policy relevance\" category indicates its alignment with ongoing discussions around Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), suggesting that it serves as an important albeit underutilized resource for those examining the intersections of economics, sustainability, and meaning. Its pedagogical strength may cultivate prospective discourse among students and educators concerned with these crucial topics.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the current absence of citations, the inferred evidential connections to commercial platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads speak to the book's potential market presence. This commercial linkage, if utilized effectively, could enhance its visibility and scholarly uptake within academic circles, furthering dialogue about the subject matter the book addresses.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In conclusion, while \"The Economy and Meaningfulness\" has yet to permeate the academic landscape significantly, its foundational hypotheses around sustainable practices and meaningful economic engagement present opportunities for educators and policymakers. Engagement with this work could stimulate discussions necessary for addressing the ethical dimensions of economic paradigms in both curricular and public policy frameworks.</p>",
